\par\plain {\f0\fs36 How To Use this Template}
\par\pard\plain \li720\fi0\sl360\slmult1\qj\ltrch\loch \ls1\ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24 Edit the Title Page document to ensure it contains the correct information.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24 Create a new folder for each part of your novel at the same level as the Title Page document. Two folders have been created at that level for you, with the placeholder title \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Part\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 . You should rename these with the titles of the parts of your novel. For instance, Milan Kundera\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s }{\f0\fs24\i1 The Unbearable Lightness of Being}{\f0\fs24\i0 \hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 s first part is entitled \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 PART ONE: }{\f0\fs24\i1 Lightness and Weight}{\f0\fs24\i0 \hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 . In that example, you would name the part, \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Lightness and Weight\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  (the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Part One\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  will be added during Compile). You can choose not to include these titles during the Compile process.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24\i0 Create a new folder for each chapter inside the relevant \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Part\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  folder and title each folder with the name of the chapter. If you don\hich\f0 \rquote \loch\f0 t intend to use chapter names, just enter use something descriptive that tells you what the chapter is about. (You do not need to title the folders \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Chapter One\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  and so on, as chapter numbering will be taken care of automatically during the Compile process.) Some chapter folders have been created for you with the placeholder title \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Chapter\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0 .}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24\i0 Create a new text document for each scene inside the chapter folders. (Upon export, scenes will be separated with the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 #\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  character.)}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24\i0 Information about characters can be placed in the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Characters\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  folder, and information about locations can be placed in the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Places\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  folder.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24 Character and setting sketch sheets have been provided which can be used for filling out information about the people and places in your novel. These are located in the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Template Sheets\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  folder. You should not edit the documents in the \hich\f0 \ldblquote \loch\f0 Template Sheets\hich\f0 \rdblquote \loch\f0  folder directly unless you wish to change the templates (which you are free to do - you may wish to customise the sketch sheets or get rid of them entirely). Instead, select the sheet and then choose Documents > Duplicate to create a new copy of the document which you can move to its intended location and fill in with your character or setting details.}
\par\plain \ilvl0{\listtext \tab \bullet \tab }{\f0\fs24\i0 Compile your manuscript into standard manuscript format by selecting File > Compile.}
